7t9.title: Attainable optimum
7t9.clickbait: The 'attainable optimum' of an agent's preferences is the best that agent can actually do given its finite intelligence and resources (as opposed to the global maximum of those preferences).
7t9.text: The 'attainable optimum' of an agent's preferences is the most preferred option that the agent can (a) obtain using its bounded material capabilities and (b) find as an available option using its limited cognitive resources; as distinct from the theoretical global maximum of the agent's utility function.  When you run a [2r8 non-mildly-optimizing] agent, what you actually get as the resulting outcome is not the single outcome that theoretically maximizes the agent's [1fw utility function]; you rather get that agent's attainable optimum of its [18t expectation] of that utility function.  A preference framework's 'attainable optimum' is what you get in practice when somebody runs the corresponding agent.
